No... a large portion of this board's posters have problems with anons. That don't make a unanimous community decision.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No offense to Fimble, who does a great job and devotes alot of time and energy to our community, for free I might add, but the final decision would be up to the community.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Amen to that!  I certainly don't want you folks to think of this community as mine. It's yours to run however you want, but I don't mind acting as a bit of a roit control officer that steps in and says &quot;this don't sound right&quot; when the masses want something done without thinking it through. This feels like one of those times to me.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Just a footnote here:If a problem arose out of anon ,the matter could be rectified by doing an IP check to make sure at least the Same person wasn't chainbooking.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
This is correct. If you suspect an anon is chain-booking, I can check the IP to verify it.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Especially since we can't even know if these raids are REAL.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
And somehow just because someone posts a raid with a name on it, it somehow makes it real?<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I just tried to reserve PoF since no one was on the calendar for the day and time, and couldn't because an ANON poster reserved it already I was told.How about the fact that I wasted my time posting here and on MY msg board trying to set this up?Not a big deal but if I had not checked the MT board later today I would not have known this and possibly not been able to secure a spot because i had already thought I had one.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
If I read this right, this has nothing to do with anon posters. You simply shouldn't plan a raid beyond it being tentative until  you first reserve that spot on the calendar. Yes, it sucks to plan it all out and get your guild all ready to raid only to find out the zone is already reserved, but quite frankly it's your own fault.<br>
<br>
<br>
With the release of PoP, it makes it too easy for individual groups to go into the planes and hunt. That means the person reserving a zone is no longer the raid leader who is intimately aware of the calendar rules, it now means any person in the community who heard anecdotally that there's a calendar out there is the one posting. The calendar rules aren't posted on the calendar itself, they're &quot;hidden&quot; in this Schedule forum. My fear is that if I start deleting anon postings, then the group leader will become frustrated and simply quit using the calendar. Which would lead to frequently empty zones for the mid-level guilds that want to raid there. yes, it does mean the calendar has to be watched closer for those with malicious intent, but I feel that's do-able and no reason to disallow anons when the consequences could be worse. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/bmtboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=karal2>Karal2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>QHills and Clueless</span><br>  Posts: 28<br> <font color=#628CBC>(5/7/03 11:46:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=380.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Anon calendar postings...</span><hr size=1> Thanks for the reply Fimble. I trust that you will keep an eye out for &quot;anon abuse&quot; and deal with it if it arises. Which is good enough for me. Thanks again Fimble for taking the time and energy to provide this community with a good resource.  <p>Gorte McGinty<br>
